items.statement:
If $(j, k)$ is a pair of nonnegative integers, then exactly one of the following statements holds:
(i) $(j, k)$ is equivalent to $(m, 0)$ for a unique $m \in \mathbb{Z}_{>0}$;
(ii) $(j, k)$ is equivalent to $(0, m)$ for a unique $m \in \mathbb{Z}_{>0}$;
(iii) $(j, k)$ is equivalent to $(0, 0)$.
